{
  "text": "Choline and its derivatives have been identified in several microalgal species or have shown functions to microalgal physiology [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . For example, 0.001 to 0.32% of the dry weight of microalgal species (for example, Chlorophyta, Rhodophyta, Phaeophyta, and Euglenophyta) is composed of choline. Synthetic choline derivatives such as choline chloride and (2-chloroethyl) trimethylammonium chloride are potent in increasing lipid contents of microalgal species [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Our current research distinguished two kinds of modes of action for choline and its derivatives. Briefly, they have achieved similar effects on the accumulation of total lipids as well as ALA but at different dose levels. The effective doses of acetylcholine are at least tenfold lower than those of choline and its other derivatives. We hypothesized that acetylcholine might function as a signaling molecule, while choline and its other derivatives function as nutrient molecules. More work is required to elucidate the underlying mechanisms.",
  "citation_candidates": [
